# Java Code Style Rules

## If Statements

Always use braces for if statements, even single-line returns:

```java
// ✅ Good
if (player == null) {
  return;
}

// ❌ Bad
if (player == null) return;
```

## Spacing Rules

### After If Blocks
Add an empty line after an if block before the next statement:

```java
// ✅ Good
if (player == null) {
  return;
}

doSomething();

// ❌ Bad
if (player == null) {
  return;
}
doSomething();
```

### Variables Before If Checks
Do NOT add an empty line between a variable declaration and its related if check:

```java
// ✅ Good
Player player = event.getPlayer();
if (player == null) {
  return;
}

// ❌ Bad
Player player = event.getPlayer();

if (player == null) {
  return;
}
```

### Combined Example

```java
public void onEvent(SomeEvent event) {
  Player player = event.getPlayer();
  if (player == null) {
    return;
  }

  Location location = player.getLocation();
  if (location == null) {
    return;
  }

  doSomething(player, location);
}
```

## Variable Extraction

Extract method calls into variables before using them in method calls:

```java
// ✅ Good
Player player = event.getPlayer();
Location location = event.getRightClicked().getLocation();
if (checkPermission(player, location, Permission.BUILD)) {
  return;
}

// ❌ Bad
if (checkPermission(event.getPlayer(), event.getRightClicked().getLocation(), Permission.BUILD)) {
  return;
}
```

## Javadoc

### When to Use
- Add javadoc to ALL methods (public, private, protected)
- Do NOT add javadoc to event handlers/listeners (methods with @EventHandler)
- Include @param for each parameter
- Include @return if method returns something

```java
// ✅ Good - Javadoc on private method
/**
 * Check if a player has permission to perform an action at a location
 *
 * @param player The player performing the action
 * @param location The location of the action
 * @param permission The permission to check
 * @return true if the player has permission, false otherwise
 */
private boolean checkPermission(Player player, Location location, Permission permission) {
  // ...
}

// ✅ Good - Javadoc on public method
/**
 * Save all currently loaded team worlds
 */
public void saveAllWorlds() {
  // ...
}

// ✅ Good - No javadoc on listener
@EventHandler
public void onBlockBreak(BlockBreakEvent event) {
  // ...
}

// ❌ Bad - Javadoc on listener
/**
 * Handles block break events
 */
@EventHandler
public void onBlockBreak(BlockBreakEvent event) {
  // ...
}
```

## Inline Comments

Add inline comments to explain what code blocks do. Comments help other developers understand the logic:

### When to Use
- Before code blocks that perform a specific action
- Before conditional logic that isn't immediately obvious
- Before loops explaining what they iterate over
- Do NOT comment obvious one-liners

```java
/**
 * Check for inactive worlds and queue them for unload
 */
private void checkInactiveWorlds() {
  Instant now = Instant.now();
  Duration threshold = Duration.ofMinutes(Config.WORLD_INACTIVITY_THRESHOLD_MINUTES.toInt());

  for (World world : Bukkit.getWorlds()) {
    // Skip non-team worlds
    if (!isTeamWorld(world)) {
      continue;
    }

    String worldName = world.getName();
    if (world.getPlayers().isEmpty()) {
      // World is empty, check if we should start tracking or unload
      Instant emptyTimestamp = emptyWorldTimestamps.get(worldName);
      if (emptyTimestamp == null) {
        // Start tracking this world as empty
        emptyWorldTimestamps.put(worldName, now);
      } else if (Duration.between(emptyTimestamp, now).compareTo(threshold) >= 0) {
        // World has been empty long enough, queue for unload
        queueWorldUnload(worldName);
        emptyWorldTimestamps.remove(worldName);
      }
    } else {
      // World has players, remove from empty tracking
      emptyWorldTimestamps.remove(worldName);
    }
  }
}

/**
 * Toggle a permission for the current role
 *
 * @param permission The permission to toggle
 */
private void togglePermission(TeamPermission permission) {
  // Get a mutable copy of current permissions for this role
  List<TeamPermission> currentPermissions = new ArrayList<>(
    team.getRolePermissions().getOrDefault(role, new ArrayList<>())
  );

  // Toggle the permission (add if missing, remove if present)
  if (currentPermissions.contains(permission)) {
    currentPermissions.remove(permission);
  } else {
    currentPermissions.add(permission);
  }

  // Save the updated permissions
  team.getRolePermissions().put(role, currentPermissions);
}
```

## Comment Banners

Do NOT use comment banners/separators:

```java
// ❌ Bad
// ==================== BUILD PERMISSION ====================

// ❌ Bad
// ---------- Getters ----------

// ❌ Bad
/* ===== SECTION ===== */
```

## Logger Messages

Use `String.format()` for logger messages with variables:

```java
// ✅ Good
plugin.getLogger().info(String.format("Loaded world %s for team %s", worldName, teamName));

// ❌ Bad
plugin.getLogger().info("Loaded world " + worldName + " for team " + teamName);
```

## Singleton getInstance() Pattern

Avoid calling `ClassName.getInstance()` repeatedly throughout a class. If you need the instance multiple times, pass it through the constructor or store it as a field.

### When getInstance() is OK
- Single use in a class (one-off access)
- In static utility methods

```java
// ✅ OK - Single field initialization
public class MyCommand {
  private final MyPlugin plugin = MyPlugin.getInstance();
}
```

### When to Use Constructor Injection

```java
// ❌ Bad - Multiple getInstance() calls
public class SomeManager {
  
  public void doSomething() {
    MyPlugin.getInstance().getLogger().info("Starting...");
    MyPlugin.getInstance().getOtherManager().process();
  }
  
  public void doAnotherThing() {
    MyPlugin.getInstance().getLogger().info("Done!");
  }
}

// ✅ Good - Pass through constructor
public class SomeManager {
  
  private final MyPlugin plugin;
  
  public SomeManager(MyPlugin plugin) {
    this.plugin = plugin;
  }
  
  public void doSomething() {
    plugin.getLogger().info("Starting...");
    plugin.getOtherManager().process();
  }
  
  public void doAnotherThing() {
    plugin.getLogger().info("Done!");
  }
}
```

### For Listeners

```java
// ❌ Bad - getInstance() in constructor and methods
public class MyListener implements Listener {
  
  private final SomeManager manager;
  
  public MyListener() {
    this.manager = MyPlugin.getInstance().getSomeManager();
  }
  
  @EventHandler
  public void onEvent(SomeEvent event) {
    MyPlugin.getInstance().getLogger().info("Event fired!");
  }
}

// ✅ Good - Store plugin reference
public class MyListener implements Listener {
  
  private final MyPlugin plugin;
  private final SomeManager manager;
  
  public MyListener(MyPlugin plugin) {
    this.plugin = plugin;
    this.manager = plugin.getSomeManager();
  }
  
  @EventHandler
  public void onEvent(SomeEvent event) {
    plugin.getLogger().info("Event fired!");
  }
}
```

### Rule of Thumb
- 1 call to `getInstance()` → OK as field initializer
- 2+ calls to `getInstance()` → Pass through constructor

## Custom Events

Custom events follow the Bukkit event pattern with a static `HandlerList`.

### Base Event Class (Optional)

If you have related events, create a base class:

```java
@Getter
public abstract class MyBaseEvent extends Event {

  private final MyData data;

  public MyBaseEvent(MyData data) {
    this.data = data;
  }

  public MyBaseEvent(MyData data, boolean async) {
    super(async);
    this.data = data;
  }
}
```

### Concrete Event Class

```java
/**
 * Called when something happens
 */
@Getter
public class MyActionEvent extends MyBaseEvent {

  private static final HandlerList HANDLERS = new HandlerList();

  private final UUID actorId;

  public MyActionEvent(MyData data, UUID actorId) {
    super(data);
    this.actorId = actorId;
  }

  @Override
  public @NotNull HandlerList getHandlers() {
    return HANDLERS;
  }

  public static HandlerList getHandlerList() {
    return HANDLERS;
  }
}
```

### Cancellable Event

```java
/**
 * Event fired when a player does something.
 * Cancelling this event will prevent the action.
 */
@Getter
public class MyCancellableEvent extends Event implements Cancellable {

  private static final HandlerList HANDLERS = new HandlerList();

  private final Player player;

  @Setter
  private List<ItemStack> rewards;

  @Setter
  private boolean cancelled = false;

  public MyCancellableEvent(Player player, List<ItemStack> rewards) {
    this.player = player;
    this.rewards = rewards;
  }

  @Override
  public HandlerList getHandlers() {
    return HANDLERS;
  }

  public static HandlerList getHandlerList() {
    return HANDLERS;
  }
}
```

### Event Pattern:
- Always include class-level javadoc describing when the event is fired
- Use `@Getter` on the class, `@Setter` only on modifiable fields
- Static `HANDLERS` field with `getHandlers()` and `getHandlerList()` methods
- Fire events using `Bukkit.getPluginManager().callEvent(new MyEvent(...))`

## Lombok Usage

- Use `@Getter` from Lombok for getters
- Never use `@Setter` on classes - write setters manually when needed
- `@Setter` on individual fields is OK for event properties that should be modifiable
